rComments: Amazing professor. He can answer any question you throw at him. Exams are really difficult in terms of length and concepts. He really gets you to think! Overall, great experience if you actually want to learn.

Honestly I really liked Ashvin as a prof. His slides were fairly clear with insightful questions/comments in the "notes" section. He also redesigned the labs this year so they're not as brutal, which was good. His tests were very tough, but I liked the course material so I studied hard & did well. I feel like he could give better feedback though.
Final exam in Fall 2015 was brutal...
Exam questions are tricky and way harder than the winter version. Ding Yuan' section is nicer and fair to the average student. Avoid Goel's section if you can.
- some labs are really simple and some are hard  - Attend lectures  and do labs and you will be fine - power point lectures - big improvement over notepad lectures - tricky exams
- lectures are worthless - teaches to the top of the class - beware his talking: he takes 1 hour to say what could be done in 15 min.

Bad lectures and notes are worse. He thinks the class is as smart as he his and so he teaches at a very fast pace with little examples. In reality though, probably 80% of the class is totally lost. Not to mention he makes really, really hard tests.

Notes are disgustingly terrible. Worst I have ever seen. I used notes from other professors from the same course  along with youtube videos to replace his notes completely. Learnt things 200% faster. His teaching methods in class are equally as bad and seems to teach to the top 10% of class using the terrible notes. No good analogies, or diagrams.

Really abominable. Teaches on a bloody text editor! I attended every single lecture and still did not understand the course. Labs are long and difficult. Kept the deadline for a big lab on the day of the midterm itself, ridiculous. And another deadline just a week later. Workload is too high. Would never take a course by this prof.

He is proud of the fact that this course is the hardest in your undergrad. The labs are intense. He answers all questions clearly but does not cover in detail even when the exams are highly detailed and long.

Other than giving you a general overview of how to approach the lab, you will get nothing useful from. His exams are absolutely brutal and attending his lectures did not help with solving anything on the tests. Do yourself a favor and take the Winter version of OS.
The answer to if he's good is yes and no :P His expectations are often too high and the explanation for  lab is not sufficient. He is really knowledgeable and fun to talk to.
He is very strict. If you are good at the subject, then you'll be okay, otherwise you'll have trouble.
He forgets to be polite to students and has trouble understanding that getting angry at people is not a good way to get them to become enthusiastic about the subjects he teaches.
His OS course sucks. The exam is tediously long, with many short answers --- make you feel like taking an English exam. The labs are very time consuming.
Not a good note writer in lectures, but he's great to ask questions to after class or in tutorials.
No Comments
I hate C++ but he has great notes and speaks very clearly. Kinda cute, too.Beware quizzes, though.
Knows his stuff, good teacher
favourite answer to questions: "i'll get back to you on that one"  but he sort of tries to teach, messy notes on board
His answer to everything, "...Use the debugger...!" Too nervous, ants up his pants....
